			<div class="et_pb_slide et_pb_slide_7 et_pb_bg_layout_light et_pb_media_alignment_center">
				
				
				<div class="et_pb_container clearfix">
					<div class="et_pb_slider_container_inner">
						
						<div class="et_pb_slide_description">
							<h2 class="et_pb_slide_title">8 of 18</h2>
				<div class="et_pb_slide_content"><p>&nbsp;</p>
<blockquote>
<p style="text-align: left;">The State Department and other people always knew that they could bring people to Chicago. That was because they would get the best reception of all, the most lavish dinners, and the biggest parades. That was because they knew they could count on Richard J. Daley to put on a good performance. With New York, there was the first time around with the astronauts, sure. But then, after the second, third, and fourth ones, they didn&#8217;t. Chicago always still got them because we still put on a good show. He just loved showing off his city.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>Ed Bedore, City Budget Director,</em></p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>May 18, 2009</em></p>
</blockquote>
<div id="attachment_1106" style="width: 390px" class="wp-caption alignleft"><a href="https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0069_0002_001.jpg" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><img class="wp-image-1106" src="https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0069_0002_001-1024x799.jpg" alt="Richard J. Daley, Judge Abraham Lincoln Marovitz, and David Ben-Gurion, Prime Minister of Israel, undated" width="380" height="297" srcset="https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0069_0002_001-1024x799.jpg 1024w, https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0069_0002_001-300x234.jpg 300w, https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0069_0002_001-1080x843.jpg 1080w, https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0069_0002_001.jpg 1500w" sizes="(max-width: 380px) 100vw, 380px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Richard J. Daley, Judge Abraham Lincoln Marovitz, and David Ben-Gurion, Prime Minister of Israel, undated. RJD_04_01_0069_0002_001</p></div>
<div id="attachment_1101" style="width: 398px" class="wp-caption alignright"><a href="https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0053_0007_002.jpg" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><img class="wp-image-1101" src="https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0053_0007_002-1024x814.jpg" alt="Richard J. Daley with Sen. Percy and Egyptian President Anwar Sadat" width="388" height="309" srcset="https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0053_0007_002-1024x814.jpg 1024w, https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0053_0007_002-300x238.jpg 300w, https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0053_0007_002-1080x858.jpg 1080w, https://rjd.library.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/13/2015/05/RJD_04_01_0053_0007_002.jpg 1500w" sizes="(max-width: 388px) 100vw, 388px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Richard J. Daley (at podium) with Senator Charles Percy (left) and President of Egypt, Anwar Sadat (middle) raising their glasses in a toast, 1975. RJD_04_01_0053_0007_002</p></div></div>
							
